  <h2>Binary verification</h2>
  <p>Every release binary ships with a detached GPG signature (<code>.asc</code> file). To verify:</p>

  <h3>1. Import the ostk signing key</h3>
  <p>The public key (<code>prime.asc</code>) is in the <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai">os-tack/ostk.ai</a> repository.</p>
  <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/os-tack/ostk.ai/main/prime.asc | gpg --import</code></pre>

  <h3>2. Verify the binary</h3>
  <pre><code>gpg --verify ostk-darwin-arm64.asc ostk-darwin-arm64</code></pre>
  <p>You should see <code>Good signature from "ostk.ai &lt;contact@ostk.ai&gt;"</code>. If verification fails, do not run the binary.</p>

  <h3>3. Make it executable</h3>
  <pre><code>chmod +x ostk-darwin-arm64
mv ostk-darwin-arm64 /usr/local/bin/ostk</code></pre>

  <h2>Signing chain</h2>
  <p>The root GPG key (<code>contact@ostk.ai</code>) certifies the CI signing key. The CI key signs release binaries. Users verify against the root key. One chain, fully offline-verifiable. See <a href="/governance">Governance</a> for the full trust model.</p>

